FILE: /tmp/llm-wiki-research/07-academic.md

VERDICT (5 lines):
1. CLAIM 1 (fine-tuned embeddings required): NOT consensus — overstated practitioner opinion. Hosted embeddings (Voyage/OpenAI/Cohere) + reranking is the recommended Day-1 path; fine-tuning is a conditional Day-2 optimization (10–30% gain in niche domains), and reranking gives 20–30% for 1/10th the effort. MongoDB angle confirmed: Voyage AI offers white-glove custom fine-tuned models usable natively in Atlas Vector Search, plus BYO embeddings and native $rerank.
2. CLAIM 2 (arXiv paper): VERIFIED — arXiv:2606.24535, "Governed Shared Memory for Multi-Agent LLM Systems," Margalit/Cohen-Inger/Avram/Taig/Margalit (Caura.ai + BGU), submitted 23 Jun 2026. Formalizes fleet-memory problem with four governance primitives (scoped retrieval, temporal supersession via supersedes_id, provenance tracking, policy-governed propagation), implemented in MemClaw (pgvector/Postgres, NOT MongoDB), benchmarked with ArgusFleet. All four primitives map cleanly onto MongoDB Atlas for a company-brain; authority weighting via trust tiers + writer identity, not numeric scores.
3. CLAIM 3 (bidirectional wiki↔code intent layer): real but fragmented prior art; no single mature OSS does the full loop. Tessl (Spec-as-Source + OpenSpec drift gates) and Augment Cosmos (Living Specs) are closest production matches; Specmatic (Apache 2.0) is the mature OSS for contract-based bidirectional sync. Aider/Claude Code intent files are largely one-way. MDD, OpenAPI-as-intent, C4 are conceptual ancestors. Tal's "auto-wiki is one-way" framing is accurate; the bidirectional loop is the active frontier, not a solved shipped product.
4. REUSABLE FOR MONGODB: adopt F=(A,M,G,P,T) framing; implement supersedes_id + status lifecycle (no in-place deletes); attach writer_agent + derived_from + reasoning_trace metadata; enforce nested scopes (agent⊑team⊑tenant) on every query path; add contradiction detection before dedup gating (their pipeline bug).
5. GAPS: no controlled benchmark of fine-tuned vs hosted+reranker on a shared enterprise corpus; arXiv paper is single-service measurement (MemClaw), generalizability to MongoDB is architectural inference; IntentFlow/Falconer/CocoIndex appear only in secondary sources (unverified).
